-# Test Execution Blocker Report Implementation Plan
-
-> **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development (recommended) or superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task. Steps use checkbox (`- [ ]`) syntax for tracking.
-
-**Goal:** Make every actual `run-tests --run` outcome of `blocked` produce a direct-cause JSON/Markdown blocker report, surface that report and the deterministic next action in the CLI, and guide the user from VS Code without treating exit code `35` as an opaque process failure.
-
-**Architecture:** The Python execution core owns blocker meaning and publication. It reuses the test-input form's stable field location and unresolved-value rules, normalizes only direct causes into a registered artifact, writes immutable run files plus latest workspace views, and keeps the terminal test outcome unchanged if explanatory publication fails. The VS Code extension consumes and verifies the structured CLI envelope and blocker artifact, opens the Markdown view once per run, restores state from validated latest-run metadata, and renders stable action codes without deriving causes itself.
-
-**Tech Stack:** Python 3.12 standard library, dataclasses, `jsonschema` draft 2020-12, existing unitTestRunner contract and execution layers, VS Code Extension API `^1.85.0`, TypeScript `^5.4.5`, Node 20, `node:test`, PowerShell 5.1-compatible Windows distribution scripts.
-
-## Global Constraints
-
-- Generate blocker reports only for an actual `run-tests --run` result whose canonical terminal outcome is exactly `blocked`.
-- Preserve `EXIT_TESTS_BLOCKED = 35`; a blocked test run is not a test failure or an internal error.
-- Generate no blocker report for `failed`, `inconclusive`, `timed_out`, `cancelled`, `passed`, or `planned` outcomes.
-- `run-tests --plan` must neither create nor remove blocker-report state.
-- The Python execution core is the only source of blocker meaning; the VS Code extension must not derive blocker causes from warning text or TestSpec content.
-- A successfully generated blocked report must contain at least one blocker; use `execution_blocked_unknown` only when no specialized direct cause can be identified.
-- Include only direct blockers that contributed to the current blocked outcome; exclude unrelated formal review work and informational warnings.
-- Reuse the test-input editor's stable item IDs, confirmation state, JSON Pointers, and unresolved-value rules. Do not add a second TestSpec traversal or placeholder interpretation.
-- One unresolved required leaf is one blocker. A fully concrete but unconfirmed execution-blocking parent is one `unconfirmed_test_input` blocker.
-- Deduplicate on `code + case_id + item_id + control_name + source_artifact + source_pointer`.
-- Sort by prerequisite category, then `case_id`, `item_id`, `control_name`, `source_pointer`, and `code`; assign `BLK-001`, `BLK-002`, and so on only after sorting.
-- Store immutable history at `runs/<run_id>/test_execution_blockers.json` and `.md`.
-- Store latest views at `reports/test_execution_blockers.json` and `.md` only when the latest actual run is blocked.
-- A later actual non-blocked run removes only the latest views and VS Code state; it never deletes historical run files.
-- The immutable run JSON is the canonical blocker artifact. Markdown and `reports/` copies are views.
-- Register `artifact_kind = "test_execution_blocker_report"` at `schema_version = "1.0.0"` and package its schema in wheels, bundled executables, and distributions.
-- `reports/latest_run.json.blocker_report` is optional and appears only when canonical blocker JSON publication succeeded.
-- Blocker publication failures must not change the real terminal outcome. They add diagnostics, suppress stale latest views, and retain exit code `35`.
-- Keep the in-memory blocker count and primary action in the CLI envelope even if report publication partially fails; include only paths that were successfully written.
-- Treat exit code `35` as a handled VS Code domain outcome only when the command is `run-tests --run` and the v1 JSON envelope parses with `outcome = blocked` and `exit_code = 35`.
-- Numeric exit code `35` alone is never sufficient. Malformed or unstructured output remains a normal CLI error.
-- Report-path verification is a separate gate for auto-open. A valid blocked envelope with no verified Markdown remains a handled blocked outcome with diagnostics and no open-report button.
-- Auto-open a verified Markdown report at most once per run ID. Closing the tab does not remove the Workflow action.
-- Restore VS Code state only when latest-run metadata, execution outcome, run ID, artifact kind, schema, execution-report reference, SHA-256, and workspace containment all match.
-- `source_artifact`, executable references, and log references exposed for navigation must be normalized workspace-relative paths without `..`.
-- Bound `current_value` to 2,048 Unicode code points, diagnostic messages to 4,096, and runner log excerpts to 8,192; set `truncated = true` when any bound is applied.
-- Do not copy complete product source files or complete unrestricted logs into the blocker artifact.
-- Keep existing execution-report fields and existing consumers backward compatible.
-- Do not automatically modify TestSpec, confirm review items, regenerate the harness, build, or rerun tests.
-- Do not implement suite-level blocker aggregation in this increment.
-- Python runtime code remains standard-library-only; test-only dependencies remain in the existing test extra.
-- Generated C and build workspaces remain C90/VC6 compatible. This feature must not introduce product-source writes.
-- `scripts/build_distribution.ps1` must run on Windows PowerShell 5.1 without PowerShell 7-only syntax.
-
